ce:section.ce:para:
In this research, all the CA measurements are done using the sessile drop method. Drop shape tensiometer (interfacial tension700-32175) is used to measure the CA (Fig. 3
                           ). In this experimental study, three saltwaters (SE, low salinity, and FMW), three Si-CQDs nano-particle solutions, four types of temperature (298.15°K, 323.15°K, 352.15°K, and 373.15°K) and four types of pressure (14.7 psig, 1000 psig, 2000 psig, and 3000 psig) were used. Also, this study identified 100,300,500 ppm Si-CQDs as effective concentrations. Therefore, CA tests were run with the 100 ppm Si-CQDs NMs in a saltwater solution. Each test was reiterated three times. On the other hand, oil/saltwater interfacial tension measurements were made. In this regard, Fig. 4
                            reports the step-by-step process of CA measurement.

The results showed that Si-CQDs altered the CR surface from oil-wet to water-wet. Jafarbeigi et al. (2021) [5] indicated that NFs tend to form thin wedges, and the wedges are driven by disjoining pressure. In this study, to evaluate the performance of 100 ppm Si-CQDs + SE in the cores, the first concentration of 100 ppm Si-CQDs was prepared and then coreflood experiments were done to EOR (Fig. 19
                           ). On the other hand, for determining the amount of oil produced, brine and 100 ppm Si-CQDs + SE were injected after saturating the cores with crude oil. Fig. 19 indicates the cumulative oil recovery versus the volume of injection pores gained from the coreflood experiments for 100 ppm Si-CQDs + SE. The breakthrough in the flooding process with brine for cores 1 and 2 was 47 % and 49 %, respectively. Generally, the calculated values of the oil recovery are reported in Table 6
                           . After calculating the values, it can be said that the ratio of oil recovery via the flooding process of the 100 ppm Si-CQDs + SE to total oil recovery is 24 % (core 1) and 23 % (core 2), respectively.
